<section class="page">
  <h2>1. How The House Will Actually Be Used</h2>
  <div class="grid2">
    <div class="box">
      <h3>Daily / regular use</h3>
      <ul>
        <li>Parents will primarily use the ground floor throughout the year.</li>
        <li>Traditional Himachali kitchen will be the main daily-use space.</li>
        <li>Modern support kitchen will sit adjacent to the traditional kitchen.</li>
        <li>Family dining and baithak area will be used daily.</li>
        <li>Existing family house can continue serving some functions including pooja room and additional accommodation.</li>
      </ul>
    </div>
    <div class="box">
      <h3>Occasional use</h3>
      <ul>
        <li>Master bedroom and Zain's bedroom will be on the first floor.</li>
        <li>Guest rooms on the third floor will be used occasionally.</li>
        <li>The full family is expected to use the house for approximately 60 days per year.</li>
        <li>Priority: practicality, durability and ease of maintenance.</li>
      </ul>
    </div>
  </div>
</section>

<section class="page">
  <h2>2. Project Vision</h2>
  <div class="grid2">
    <div class="box">
      <h3>Core idea</h3>
      <p>Create a family home that feels warm, elegant and rooted in Himachal, while borrowing the best proportions and softness of Portuguese / European country homes.</p>
      <ul>
        <li>Multi-generational family use</li>
        <li>Comfortable for parents</li>
        <li>Beautiful but not flashy</li>
        <li>Easy to maintain when not fully occupied</li>
        <li>Designed to age well over 20–30 years</li>
      </ul>
    </div>
    <div class="box">
      <h3>Design keywords</h3>
      <ul>
        <li>Warm</li>
        <li>Timeless</li>
        <li>Natural light</li>
        <li>Kitchen-centred</li>
        <li>Covered verandahs</li>
        <li>Stone + wood + plaster</li>
        <li>Low maintenance</li>
      </ul>
    </div>
  </div>
  <div class="note"><b>One-line brief:</b> A timeless Himachali family home inspired by Portuguese country estates and English countryside interiors, centred around a large traditional Himachali kitchen with chulha, adjacent modern support kitchen, family baithak/dining space, abundant natural light, covered verandahs and long-term practicality.</div>
</section>

<section class="page">
  <h2>3. Site Context & Planning</h2>
  <div class="grid2">
    <div>
      <p><b>Site:</b> Family-owned land in Patta Barawari, Solan District, near Tapalori Durga Temple area.</p>
      <p><b>Existing house:</b> The old family house remains on the property and does not need to be demolished. The new house should complement it rather than duplicate every function.</p>
      <h3>Site priorities</h3>
      <ul>
        <li>Orient main family spaces toward best light and views</li>
        <li>Create easy access between house, verandah and garden</li>
        <li>Keep landscaping natural and low-maintenance</li>
        <li>Allow parking and simple circulation</li>
        <li>Preserve scope for fruit trees / kitchen garden</li>
      </ul>
    </div>
    <div class="box">
      <h3>Area direction</h3>
      <table>
        <tr><th>Component</th><th>Target</th></tr>
        <tr><td>Built-up area</td><td>3,500–4,000 sq ft</td></tr>
        <tr><td>Garden / outdoor living</td><td>800–1,000 sq ft</td></tr>
        <tr><td>Overall developed experience</td><td>Approx. 4,500–5,000 sq ft</td></tr>
        <tr><td>Budget target</td><td>₹75 lakh–₹1 Cr incl. interiors</td></tr>
      </table>
    </div>
  </div>
</section>

<section class="page">
  <h2>4. Exterior Reference Board</h2>
  <div class="grid3">
    {fig("exterior_1","Main exterior massing","Use as overall scale/massing direction; light colours, practical roof and limited glazing.")}
    {fig("exterior_2","Portuguese / estate character","Warm plaster, roof overhangs, verandahs and simple classical edges.")}
    {fig("hero","Proposed family home concept","Use for overall family-home feeling; avoid resort-scale execution.")}
  </div>
  <div class="grid2" style="margin-top:22px">
    <div class="box do">
      <h3>Use</h3>
      <ul>
        <li>Warm plaster walls: cream / off-white / soft beige</li>
        <li>Local stone detailing at plinth and landscape walls</li>
        <li>Sloping roof with deep overhangs</li>
        <li>Covered verandahs and shaded outdoor sitting</li>
        <li>Arches at selected feature points</li>
      </ul>
    </div>
    <div class="box dont">
      <h3>Avoid</h3>
      <ul>
        <li>Full glass façades</li>
        <li>Too many roof junctions</li>
        <li>Overly formal mansion look</li>
        <li>High-maintenance exterior timber everywhere</li>
      </ul>
    </div>
  </div>
</section>

<section class="page">
  <h2>5. Windows & Doors</h2>
  <div class="grid3">
    {fig("window","Actual window / door reference","Tall arched French doors for living, dining or feature spaces.")}
    {fig("ceiling","Timber ceiling / framed opening mood","Use selectively, not throughout the house.")}
    {fig("interior_1","Garden-facing framed windows","Preferred over continuous wall-to-wall glass.")}
  </div>
  <div class="note"><b>Principle:</b> Lots of light, not lots of glass.</div>
  <div class="grid2" style="margin-top:20px">
    <div class="box">
      <h3>Recommended</h3>
      <ul>
        <li>Large framed windows</li>
        <li>French doors opening to verandah/garden</li>
        <li>Deep window reveals</li>
        <li>Dark bronze, walnut or sage green frames</li>
        <li>Operable windows for cross-ventilation</li>
      </ul>
    </div>
    <div class="box">
      <h3>Limit / avoid</h3>
      <ul>
        <li>Continuous glass walls</li>
        <li>Large glass roofs</li>
        <li>Custom panels that are hard to replace locally</li>
        <li>Overly industrial black-frame look</li>
      </ul>
    </div>
  </div>
</section>

